article.description: Allison Feaster scored 18 points and Andrea Stinson added 14 as the Sting completed a perfect three-game road trip with a 71-58 victory over the Liberty in a rematch of the Eastern Conference finals from a year ago.
article.headline: Charlotte vying for second East spot
article.linkText: Sting get past Liberty, keep playoff pace with Mystics
article.story:
NEW YORK -- Allison Feaster scored 18 points as the Charlotte
Sting beat the New York Liberty 71-58 Sunday to stay in the hunt
for the Eastern Conference's second playoff spot.

	   The Sting (17-14) are on track for a showdown with the Mystics.
Washington beat Cleveland 60-54 on Sunday night to remain tied and
will end the regular season Tuesday in Charlotte.

	   The Liberty have already clinched the East, and both Charlotte
and Washington are assured of playoff spots.

	   "We've had our struggles on the road this year, but we know
playoff-time is the time to play,'' Andrea Stinson said. "And we
are underestimated when it comes to playoff time.''

	   Crystal Robinson scored 10 of her 16 points in the first half
for the Liberty (18-13), who clinched the top playoff seed in the
East with a win over Washington Friday. Tari Phillips added 11
points.

	   Sparked by two 3-point plays each from Dawn Staley and Feaster,
Charlotte went on an 19-3 run to start the second half and take a
53-35 lead.

	   "We know the importance of playing at home, and it was a factor
tonight and will be a factor against Washington,'' Feaster said.

	   Stinson added 14 points for Charlotte and Staley had 11.

	   The Liberty didn't make their second field goal of the game
until Camille Cooper hit a turnaround jumper with 9:30 left in the
first half. But Robinson followed with a layup and a pair of
3-pointers to keep New York in the game early.

	   "We played terrible. It was embarrassing,'' Robinson said.
"Having already clinched is just an excuse. Great teams come to
play and come to beat people. We don't want to go into the playoffs
losing.''

	   Charlotte Smith dislocated her right pinky finger four minutes
into the game and did not return until the second half, when she
scored all of her nine points.
